{"slug": "wizard", "root": "wizard", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a worker of learned magic", "definition": "A wizard is a worker of *learned* magic — one whose power comes from study, books, and mastered lore rather than from a pact or an inborn gift. In the fantasy tradition the wizard is the scholarly magic-user par excellence, staff in one hand and grimoire in the other.", "history": "The word begins as an honorific: Middle English *wysard*, 'wise one' (from *wys*, 'wise,' + the agent-suffix *-ard*), meaning a sage or philosopher. Only in the 1550s does it harden toward the sinister — a man whose wisdom shades into forbidden art. Tolkien's Gandalf fixed the modern image in 1954, and Magic: The Gathering inherits it wholesale: *Wizard* is the game's largest magic-user type, 1,288 creatures strong, and skews blue — the color of knowledge.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. wizard", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "the corpus (Wizard subtype)", "where": "Corpus"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Middle English wys (‘wise’) + -ard", "first": "c. 1440 as ‘philosopher, sage’; ‘one with magic power’ by the 1550s", "note": "A wizard was first simply a wise man; the sinister magical sense is a later hardening of an honorific.", "hook": "How ‘wise guy’ became ‘spellcaster.’", "lang": "Old English"}, "essay": {"title": "Wizard: the wise man who went wrong", "dek": "The word began as a compliment. Watch a sage curdle into a suspect.", "read_min": 3, "html": "<p>Magic: The Gathering has 1,288 creatures with the <em>Wizard</em> type — its single largest class of magic-user, and, tellingly, its bluest, blue being the game's color of knowledge. That is exactly right, because <strong>wizard</strong> began not as a word for power but as a word for <em>wisdom</em>. Middle English <em>wysard</em>, first recorded around 1440, joined <em>wys</em> ('wise') to the suffix <em>-ard</em>, and it meant a philosopher, a sage — a wise man, full stop.</p><p>Then it curdled. The suffix <em>-ard</em> is a souring one: it makes <em>drunkard</em>, <em>coward</em>, <em>sluggard</em>, <em>dullard</em>, and by the 1550s it was doing the same to the wise man. A <em>wizard</em> came to mean one whose wisdom had strayed into forbidden art — a knower of too much. The hardening tracks a real historical squeeze: this is the century in which England began prosecuting its 'cunning folk,' the village healers and finders whose learning, as Keith Thomas shows in <em>Religion and the Decline of Magic</em>, was recategorized from useful to illicit. The word's fall is the culture's suspicion, fossilized.</p><p>Fantasy then restored the honorific. Tolkien's Gandalf (1954) is a sage before he is a spellcaster, and the game inherits that dignity: its wizards <em>study</em>, and in Strixhaven (2021) the whole setting became a university of them. But both lives of the word survive on the cards — the revered adept and the meddler who knew too much. A wizard is, etymologically, only a wise guy; whether that is a compliment has always depended on who is saying it.</p>", "sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.vv. wizard, -ard", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "Keith Thomas, Religion and the Decline of Magic (cunning folk)", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "the corpus (Wizard creature type, color distribution)", "where": "Corpus"}]}, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 106, "oracle_total": 170, "in_flavor_cards": 100, "in_oracle_cards": 149, "name_match_count": 35, "by_variant": {"wizard": 212, "wizards": 62, "wizardry": 2}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"W": 40, "C": 23, "U": 137, "R": 56, "B": 41, "G": 18}, "by_year": {"1994": 2, "1995": 6, "1996": 1, "1997": 11, "1998": 6, "1999": 4, "2000": 3, "2001": 7, "2002": 18, "2003": 5, "2004": 4, "2005": 3, "2006": 2, "2007": 5, "2008": 7, "2009": 5, "2010": 1, "2011": 1, "2012": 1, "2013": 2, "2014": 3, "2015": 4, "2016": 2, "2017": 8, "2018": 14, "2019": 4, "2020": 47, "2021": 20, "2022": 28, "2023": 13, "2024": 8, "2025": 16, "2026": 6}}, "cards": [{"id": "3cae0e4b-1827-4ed2-832f-98f8e79941a5", "name": "Thrull Wizard", "set": "FEM", "set_name": "Fallen Empires", "released": "1994-11-01", "type_line": "Creature — Thrull Wizard", "rarity": "uncommon", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/c/4/c4e732fb-cbef-4fd8-b704-e4d513a6cf2d.jpg?1782722005", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/c/4/c4e732fb-cbef-4fd8-b704-e4d513a6cf2d.jpg?1782722005", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/fem/46/thrull-wizard?utm_source=api", "local": "img/wizard/3cae0e4b-1827-4ed2-832f-98f8e79941a5.jpg"}, {"id": "51635f96-af1d-4b33-9118-432495aaf07f", "name": "Wizards' School", "set": "HML", "set_name": "Homelands", "released": "1995-10-01", "type_line": "Land", "rarity": "uncommon", "colors": ["B", "U", "W"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/c/d/cd736532-8e98-4f4a-b48f-a66c57efcbfd.jpg?1782721549", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/c/d/cd736532-8e98-4f4a-b48f-a66c57efcbfd.jpg?1782721549", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/hml/115/wizards-school?utm_source=api", "local": "img/wizard/51635f96-af1d-4b33-9118-432495aaf07f.jpg"}, {"id": "f2902dfd-888f-4b02-b8ad-1056f0059fc3", "name": "Ertai, Wizard Adept", "set": "EXO", "set_name": "Exodus", "released": "1998-06-15", "type_line": "Legendary Creature — Human Wizard", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["U"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/9/1/91971e19-61ce-45ac-b700-9ffca5091a27.jpg?1782720805", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/9/1/91971e19-61ce-45ac-b700-9ffca5091a27.jpg?1782720805", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/exo/33/ertai-wizard-adept?utm_source=api", "local": "img/wizard/f2902df